creator: Harl A. Dalstrom & Kay Calame Dalstrom
descrip:
The October 1938 forest fire and the last frontier in the Rainy River-Lake of the Woods borderland.

From the back cover; "October 10, 1938 was Canada's Thanksgiving Day, but that warm and windy Monday brought the horror of forest fire to the Ontario-Minnesota Rainy border. Seventeen people in Dance Township, Ontario, lost their lives as did one man in International Falls, Minnesota. In addition to telling a story of disaster and near disaster, the authors examine what life was like for settlers on one of North America's last frontiers."
physdesc:
6" x 9" softcovered bound book, the cover is black with a picture of a fire burning high in the sky and burnt tree sillohettes. The title is on the front  and the authors. On the back is a desciption of the book and about the authors along with a picture of Dance township.

This is a signed copy
publisher: Rainy River District Women's Institute Museum
spinelbl: "We were not worried at Dinner Time"
subjects: The October 1938 forest fire and the last frontier in the Rainy River-Lake of the Woods borderland.
title: "We were not worried at Dinner Time"

creator: Merrie Sue Holtan
descrip:
From inside cover flap; " When Nancy Burggraf whistled, players skated to attention. Big Players. Players with face masks and hockey sticks. She has been called a hockey "guro" and "icon" by USA Today and was the first woman nominated to the United States Hockey Hall of Fame. During five decades she touched the lives of more than 40,000 hokcey players through her unique skating skills clinics. She tought some of the best in the National Hockey League and was able to connect with her players on a personal level. 
Power & Stride is the inspiring story of a woman from Roseau, Minnesota, who succeeded in a male-dominated world and changed the game of hockey forever. Those who knew Nancy treasure her for what she taught them, and they continue to pass on her legacy."
physdesc:
6.25" x 9.25" multicolored hardcover bound book with a paper protective cover.  Thre is a picture of Nancy on the cover and hockey players. There are white lines that run across the top and down the right side.  On the backcover is four picture of Nancy with kids, icecapes, hockey team and Nancy & Bernie with three hockey players. On the inside of the back cover is a DVD in a plastic pouch. 

This is a signed copy.
subjects: Book & DVD about the life of Nancy Burggraf
title: Power & Stride The Nancy Burggraf Story

He married Anna Loftness October 4, 1913.

creator: Dr. Hayden L.Stright
descrip:
Only Dr. Stright could write this book. This is because he had so much to do with making the history he chronicles. It's a story of dedicated people who struggled against great odds to lay a strong foundation for Christian cooperation in Minnesota. It deserves to be read by all who have a serious interest in understanding the background of the ecumenical movement in the state.
"Dr. Stright, in his conclusion, warns about dangers he senses in certain current ecumenical trends. Not all will share his concerns, but they deserve to be considered since they come out of a lifetime of experience as an ecumenical pioneer

descrip: 1 hard covered book, rust colored, with the lettering and picture in teal with peach accents. Picture of an old bearded man sitting on a stool holding a sail boat. The back of cover has a boy paddleing a canoe. Title is "Happy Road To Reading, Days To Remember." Authors are Katherine E. Dopp, May Pitts, S.C. Garrison and illustrated by Herbert Rudeen. The book belonged to Louis Hermansen. Robert McSounick gave Louis the book. The book contains 8 units, each with a theme. For example, the 1st unitis called "Happy Hours" because it contains selections that are enjoyable and easy to read. The second unit , "The Great Outdoors," contains selections about plants, animals and other interesting things in nature.  Some of the other units such as,"Stories of Other Days," "american Heros," and Looking at Our Country," deal with topics that are studied in school. Every unit has something to do with a person's life.

descrip: Rick Steber began writing "Tales of the Wild West" stories in 1973 for his syndicated newspaper column. He gathers information from personal interviews and research in journals, diaries, logs, letters, newspapers and books. To gain a pioneer's perspective he has hiked the Oregon Trail and paddled a canoe from the wilderness to the mouth of the Columbia River. As he crisscrosses the country gleaning material, Rick has gained an understanding of and deep personal feeling for the people and the landscape of the west.

creator: 2001 by Harold M. Lian
descrip:
Harold Lian's auto-biography (Volume 1). This book describes Harold's growing up on a farm south of Roseau during the Great Depression, his eight years attending District 51 elementary school, 4 years in Roseau High School, and his experiences during World War II. Volume 1 is closed with Harold's discharge from the U.S. Army in April 1946.

This book was not published. Harold made copies for his family and a few extra. He sent a copy of Volume 1 & 2 to RCHS in 2001 and 2009. These 2 copies belonged to Lawrence Klema.

creator: Harold Lian
descrip:
Harold Lian's auto-biography (Volume 2). This begins with Harold being discharged from the Army and resuming his education at UCLA. He married Lois in 1953. This book is for the most part an account of Harold's participation in petroleum exploration activities in countries throughout the world, in positions ranging from chief geologist of Union Oil Company of California's international division to 9 years as president of that division. His last five years were spent in Thailand where he was president and chief officer of Unocal Thailand. In 1987, he was awarded a high decoration by the King of Thailand. 

The readers may enjoy this account of the adult years of a local boy who found himself in a world of which he never even dreamed when he was growing up on a farm in Roseau County.

creator: Rev. B. M. Hofrenning
descrip: 1 "Captain Jens Munk's Septentrionalis" book written by Rev. B. M. Hofrenning. Norse Discovery of Churchill, Hudson Bay, September 7, 1619.  Septentrional, meaning "of the north", is a word that is rarely used in English but is commonly used in Latin and in the Romance languages. The term is sometimes found on maps mostly made before 1700, Early maps of North America often refer to the northern- or northwestern-most unexplored areas of the continent at "Septentrional" or "America Septentrionalis", sometimes with slightly varying spellings.[note 1] The term septentrional, actually the adjectival form of the noun septentrion, itself refers to the seven stars of the Big Dipper asterism

creator: Hazel Wahlberg       (Illustrated by Frances Karlsson)
descrip:
Seven harcovered books titled "The Northland" A History of Roseau County written by Hazel Wahlberg and illustrated by Frances Karlsson. The book is red with white design on front cover. There is a paper protector on five of the books , which gives description of book and a map of Roseau County on the back of cover. There are 224 pages


Hazel H. Wahlberg grew up in North St. Paul, Minnesota, and graduated from St. Olaf College. She was an English teacher and librarian for a number of years, and has always been interested in writing. The history of the area was a natural subject for a writing project, and she spent four and a half years in preparation of this book. Her love for Northern Minnesota and its people made it a labor of great joy and satisfaction.

Frances Karlsson, the artist was born in Peoria, Illinois, and studied commercial art in Chicago. After working for book publishers she married Einar Karlsson and the redided on a farm near Roseau where she had continued her interest in art. She did realistic paintings of the area in watercolor, and palette knife oils. Frances Karlsson's art had been presented in several art shows.

creator: Roseau County Volunteers
descrip:
2 paperback books titled "County of Roseau Centennial" 1895-1995. The cover is a commemorative poster that celebrates one hundred years of county history by depicting the "Medora" loaded with passengers, mail, and supplies on its daily run from Pelan to Roseau, Minnesota soon after the county was organized. The horse-drawn coach followed the sand ridge traveled by various Indian tribes as well as the trappers and hunters in the area. 

Marv Espe designed this cover. Marv Espe grew up on a farm near Roseau, Minnesota and has enjoyed producing works of art which reflect his rural background as well as his love of natural subjects which include woods and water as well as the creatures that live there. His art career began in 1965 after a brief five-year stint as an elementary teacher. His formal art training included time at the American Academy of Art in Chicago as well as at the Minneapolis College of Art and Design in Minneapolis, Minnesota.

From 1965 until 1977 he was employed by Jostens Inc. of Owatonna, Minnesota as staff artist in their Graphic Arts Division. In 1977, Espe with his wife Myrna and two children moved to northern Minnesota where for 20 years he was engaged in painting a wide range of local subjects as well as illustrating for numerous publishers on a free-lance basis.

In 1997 he and his wife moved to northern Wisconsin where he continues to create beautiful art. To date he has produced and sold well more than 1100 original paintings. Well over 1000 of his illustrations have also been published over the years. He has also conducted painting workshops for numerous art organizations in Minnesota, North Dakota, South Dakota and Nebraska.

His paintings have been included in many group and individual exhibitions throughout the upper midwest, and are seen in private as well as corporate collections throughout the U.S. and Canada.

National organizations that have used his art include: The Artists Magazine, The American Artist Magazine, National Arbor Day Foundation, National Wildlife Federation, National Rifle Association and others.  http://marvespeart.com/about/

323 pages

creator: Hazel Wahlberg       (Illustrated by Frances Karlsson)
descrip:
6 paperback books titled "Remembrances" Anthology of Roseau County, compiled & written by Hazel Wahlberg, edited by Valborg Tweet, and cover & sketches by Frances Karlsson. The book is red with white design on front cover. This book was compiled so that the remembrance of the foundations of Roseau County would be preserved. The subjects for the articles were chosen to present a wide variety of occupations from various areas in the county. Further consideration had to be given to availability of data, authoritative authorship, as well as the contributions each made to Roseau County. 
128 pages


Hazel H. Wahlberg grew up in North St. Paul, Minnesota, and graduated from St. Olaf College. She was an English teacher and librarian for a number of years, and has always been interested in writing. The history of the area was a natural subject for a writing project, and she spent four and a half years in preparation of this book. Her love for Northern Minnesota and its people made it a labor of great joy and satisfaction.

Frances Karlsson, the artist was born in Peoria, Illinois, and studied commercial art in Chicago. After working for book publishers she married Einar Karlsson and the redided on a farm near Roseau where she had continued her interest in art. She did realistic paintings of the area in watercolor, and palette knife oils. Frances Karlsson's art had been presented in several art shows.

creator: Michael Meuers
descrip:
Road to Ponemah: The Teachings of Larry Stillday
by Michael Meuers

Stillday was a well-known spiritual leader, healer and teacher from Red Lake Nation who touched many Ojibwe people in northern Minnesota. His words and teachings not only impacted the Native population, but people from all walks of life. He inspired thousands with his teachings about living in harmony, not only with each other, but also with nature. He passed on in May 2014, but his message survives. 
Meuers was given a spirit name by Stillday (Biidaanakwad Izhinikaazo - Gathering Cloud is His Name). He has worked in public relations for the Red Lake Band of Chippewa Indians for more than twenty years, and during this time he spearheaded the Ojibwe Language project in Bemidji, MN, which was recently recognized by National Geographic for: ... support in sustaining and enhancing the unique geographic character of the region... 
Having just finished reading, I am proud to call you my brother and found it to be absolutely awesome, heart-warming, informative, and touches ones heart in a very special way. ~Eugene Bugger McArthur, former Chairman of White Earth Nation 
https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/33636390-road-to-ponemah

Meuers lives with his wife, three cats, and a dog on a four-acre peninsula overlooking the Mississippi River just after it leaves Lake Bemidji. They have two adult daughters and two Grandchildren. He grew up in the Twin Cities moving to Minnesota's Great North Woods in his early 30's. He first lived near Northome, MN where he built a house having more time than money. A few years later he had the house moved 55 miles to it's current location on the Mississippi River near Bemidji, MN.

He worked for a local public television afiliate before taking a job with the Red Lake Band of Chippewa Indians. He has worked as a public relations person with the Band for 22 years taking photos and writing storiesabout the Red Lake Band.

He has worked in a varity of ways to help bridge Indian and Non-Indian culture of north central Minnesota, by encouraging learning, the celebration of diversity, and to open a dialog that would begin this conversation.

He spearheaded Bemidji's Ojibwe Language Project. Nearly 200 businesses and organizations withing a hundred miles of Bemidji post a variety of common signage in both English and Ojibwe through his efforts.

meuers recieved a Spirit (Indian) name in a ceremony conducted by the book's subject, Larry Stillday, in the summer of 2013. Biidaanakwad Izhinikaazo. (Gathering Cloud is His Name).

Meuers operates a blog, titled: Indian Country, Through the Eyes of an Irishman. You can find it here: http://omakakii.blogspot.com/

creator: Cris Peterson
descrip:
1 hardcovered book about French voyageurs, portage paths, trade goods, and beaver pelts. Snowshoes, birchbark canoes, wild rice, and beaver pelts. Two hundred years ago, beaver pelts were the common denominator that brought two cultures together, creating an uncommonly successful business and opening the North American continent.
In the late 1700s, the North West Company was the biggest enterprise in North America, and fur trading was its business. Furs harvested by the Indians across the continent and transported in birchbark canoes to wilderness trading posts ended up on the sleeves and hems of French princesses and Chinese emperors. Felt hats on the heads of European businessmen and military officers began as beaver pelts that were paddled through a maze of rivers and then shopped by sail to Europe. Iron tools, woolen blankets, and calico cloth manufactured in England found their way to the lodges and wigwams of Indians across North America.
The fur trade began only a few decades after Christopher Columbus first sailed west from Europe, and it continues for over three centuries. Drawing on episodes from the diaries of explorers and traders and a lifetime of experience living in the heart of what once was fur country, the author has brought to life a pivotal chapter of American history that is seldom examined. She also worked closely with experts in the field and gathered archival prints, paintings and maps in order to put faces on the many people and places involved in the fur trade's rich history

descrip:
1 paperback book of the journals of five fur traders of the Northwest.captures the day-to-day life of the fur trader during the late eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries. Long out of print and difficult to obtain, this useful book contains the authenic journals of five fur traders. 
Peter Pond, a founding partner of the North West Company, makes detailed observations of the region's native peoples. 
John Macdonell describes with care his first trip over the fur trade route through the Great Lakes and the Minnesota-Ontario border lakes to the region of Lake Winnipeg.
Archibald N. McLeod's journal tells of wintering at Fort Alexandria on the Assiniboine River. 
Hugh Faries writes of life at the North West Company's fort on the Rainy River.
John Sayer records his establishing of a trading post in the St. Croix country near the present day Pine City, Minnesota. (This diary was originally attributed to Thomas Connor, but research conducted since the has established Sayer as the true author.)
These documents offer dramatic, firsthand glimpses of the daily existence of voyageurs and Indians and detailed data on canoeing, trading practices, trade goods, and Indian customs.

creator: Grace Lee Nute
descrip: 1 paperback book Rainy River Country tells of the earliest people who passed through the region, Mongoloid men from Asia; of the mound builders who followed them; and of the Sioux Indians and, later, the Chippewa, who lived on or near the river, fishing, gathering wild rice, and hunting the elk, moose, deer, bear, caribou, and the smaller animals that roamed the valley. It reveals how traders traveled up and down the river for two centuries in quest of fortunes in furs and skins; how lighthearted voyageurs, singing their chansons, canoed over the waterway and toiled across portages with their heavy loads; and how missionaries came to heal the souls of dwellers in the wilderness. It tells of explorers who passed that way in search of the Western Sea or of routes to the Arctic; of settlers who traveled the river on their way to new homes in the West; of prospectors seeking gold; and of artists recording the face of the country in the sketchbooks. And it relates how farms were opened; how towns and villages grew up; how lumbering activities were carried on; how great industries developed; and how tourists have come in increasing numbers to that magnificent vacation land shared by the people of Minnesota and Ontario as a single, friendly community.

French Canadians who guided and paddled the canoes of explorers and fur traders, the voyageurs were experts at traversing the treacherous rapids and dangerous open waters of the canoe routes from Quebec to Montreal to the regions bordering the Great Lakes and on to the Mackenzie & Columbia Rivers. During the eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries, explorers and fur traders relied on the voyageurs to open up the vast reaches of North America to settlement and trade.

caption: The Voyageur's Highway
creator: Grace Lee Nute
descrip: 1 paperback book "The Voyageur's Highway" by Grace Lee Nute was the route from Lake Superior along inland waterways to the Minnesota north country. Countless people --- explorers, fur traders, missionaries, map makers, lumberjacks, miners, conservationists, naturalists ---were drawn to the region's woods and lakeshores. Indians, French Canadians, Yankees, Scandinavians, and Slavs all used the rich resources of the land to follow an old way of life or to find a new one. In a lively, clear style, Nute tells the fascinating story of their adventures and love of the land. "The Voyager's Highway" serves as a dependable souce of historical information on the fur trade era, the opening of the Iron Range, and the loggers' way of life.

authorx: with an introduction by W. Roger Buffalohead
caption: History of the Ojibway People
creator: William Whipple Warren (1825-1853)
descrip:
1 paperback book about the history of the Ojibway people
The author Willian W. Warren was a descendant of Richard Warren, one of the "MayFlower" pilgrims, who landed at Plymouth in 1620
This book was written in 1852 and first published in 1885, is perhaps the most important history of the Ojibway (Chippewa) People ever written. Warren, the son of an Ojibway woman and a white man, collected firsthand descriptions and stories from his relatives, tribal leaders, and aquaintances. He transcribed this oral history in terms that nineteenth-century whites could understand, focusing on warfare, tribal organization, and political leaders. Interspersed among his vivid descriptions of memorable battles is a wealth of information on the Ojibway people's customs, family life, totemic system, hunting methods, fur trade, and relations with other tribal groups and with whites. W. Roger Buffalohead's new introduction to this edition describes the complexities that make this a fascinating study.

descrip:
1 paper back book of family histories & stories as first told by Ray Mortensen. Original copyright  1996 by Marjorie Mortensen. Originally published by the author as "Ray's Stories: Stories told by Ray Mortensen about family and neighbors in Wannaska MN.
True stories of the real Norwegian - and Danish - bachelor farmers and their cousins, aunts, uncles, grandparents and neighbors.
'"A Boy From Wannaska" shines light on a northern Minnesota farming community, where first-generation Scandinavian immigrants built new lives early in the twentieth century. This memoir describes farming and household practices, and tells hilarious stories of backwoods farmers in a new enviroment: learning to drive, hunting moose, building new social institutions - and competitive potlucks at a local Lutheran Church, made of 37 souls and 7 Danes.
Marjorie Wright Mortensen collected this heritage of tales told among the children and grandchildren of Scandinavian immigrants in Roseau County. The text includes historic photos and an appendix with genealogy of the Danish forebearers and American descendants of Jens and Ellen Mortensen, who immigrated from Odense County Denmark in 1889.

In the harsh cold winters of north central United States and Canada there has always been an ever-present malicious force. A force that would drive men to devour their families. creator: Earl V. Chapin
descrip:
1 hardcovered book "Heavy Water" written by Earl V. Chapin & published in 1952 by George A. Pflaum, Publisher, Inc.
Printed & published in the United States of America. Published simultaneously in Canada by Nelson, Foster & Scott, Ltd.
192 pages. Used in Roseau High School Library.
This is a story containing all the elements calculated to hold the attention and fire the imagination of any boy. For where is the boy that is not intrigued by thoughts of canoeing on uncharted streams and hidden lakes, of making portages, of nights on the lake shores under the stars made mysterious by the cry of the loon, of strange characters in the deep woods, of Indians, and of strange tales about "heavy water" possibly betraying the whereabouts of precious uranium. All of that is here within this book. Mr. Chapin has chosen as the setting for his story a background he knows so well from having lived in it---northern Minnesota and southern Manitoba which is commonly called Lake of the Woods country----and to point out that the greatest treasures men may find are not material, he has incorporated into his story a factual account of the earliest pages of the history of Lake of the Woods.

descrip:

Lyons and Carrigan Publisher - Founded by U of Kentucky alum James Carnahan, Lyons & Carnahan published educational materials and books, mostly in the early 1900's.
Hall of Distinguished Alumni
James William Carnahan
Born in Knox County, Ky., 1870. Publisher. University of Kentucky, A.B., 1896. Died, August 25, 1958.
Following graduation from the University, he was an instructor at Berea College, Sue Bennett College, London, and taught at a number of other Kentucky schools.
He began work with the American Book Company and G & Company, educational publishers of Boston, Massachusetts, in 1900, doing editorial work and sales. In 1912, with J. A. Lyons, Carnahan organized the educational publishing house of Lyons and Carnahan in Chicago. Lyons died in 1920 and he became the sole owner of the firm. As President, he extended the business throughout the United States and the English-speaking world.
He made a substantial contribution for the renovation of the main residence at Coldstream Farm. Carnahan House, named in his honor, at one time was utilized as the alumni-faculty club of the University and later became the principal conference center for university conferences and institutes. He died in1958 only three months after Carnahan House was dedicated.
The University awarded him its Founders Day plaque, recognizing his contributions to education, in 1956. He helped write several textbooks. As an undergraduate at the University, he became an outstanding football left-tackle in the Southeastern Conference. He was President of the Kentucky Society of Chicago.


James William Carnahan was named to the Hall of Distinguished Alumni in February, 1965.
